 ✅ Binary Tree Preorder Traversal — Easy

Concept: Recursion + Helper Pattern

Created a separate helper() to pass the ans list around
Base case: root == null → stop
Order: add node first, then recurse left, then right
That "add first" is what makes it Preorder

/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> preorderTraversal(TreeNode root) {
        ArrayList<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();
        helper(root , ans);
        return ans;
    }
    public void helper(TreeNode root , List<Integer> ans){
        if(root == null) return;
        ans.add(root.val);
        helper(root.left , ans);
        helper(root.right , ans);



    }
}



✅ Lowest Common Ancestor of a Binary Tree — Medium

Concept: Post-order thinking + Bubble up

Search left and right subtrees for p and q
3 cases:

Found p or q → return it immediately
Both sides return non-null → current node is LCA
One side null → return the non-null side


The answer bubbles up from bottom to top

/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode(int x) { val = x; }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public TreeNode lowestCommonAncestor(TreeNode root, TreeNode p, TreeNode q) {
        if(root == null) return root;
        if(root == p || root == q) return root;
        TreeNode l = lowestCommonAncestor(root.left , p, q);
        TreeNode r = lowestCommonAncestor(root.right , p,q);
        if(l != null && r != null) return root;
        return (l ==null) ? r : l; 
        
    }
}

✅ Flatten Binary Tree to Linked List — Medium  

Concept: Recursion + Pointer Rewiring (Morris style)

Save left and right subtrees before touching anything
Flatten both subtrees independently first
Then attach: root.right = flattened left
Walk to the end of that chain, attach flattened right
Much cleaner than the list approach — no extra space!

class Solution {
    public static void flatten(Node root) {
        // code here
        if(root == null) return;
        Node lst = root.left;
        Node rst = root.right;
        root.left = null;
        root.right = null;
        flatten(lst);
        flatten(rst);
        root.right = lst;
        Node last = root;
        while(last.right != null){
          last =  last.right ;
        }
        last.right = rst;
        
    }
}

✅ Min Distance Between Two Nodes — Hard

Concept: LCA + Level tracking via DFS

Reused LCA logic from problem 2 ♻️
Then ran DFS from LCA, tracking depth with level
When node a found → store level in dist[0]
When node b found → store level in dist[1]
Answer = dist[0] + dist[1] (both distances from LCA)

Formula behind it:
dist(a, b) = dist(LCA→a) + dist(LCA→b)


/* A binary tree node
class Node {
    public int data;
    public Node left;
    public Node right;

    public Node(int val) {
        data = val;
        left = null;
        right = null;
    }
}
*/

class Solution {
     int findDist(Node root, int a, int b) {
      Node LCA = lca(root, a , b);
      int [] dist = {0,0};
      dfs(LCA, 0, a, b, dist);
      return dist[0] + dist[1];
        
    }
    
     Node lca(Node root, int p, int q) {
      if(root == null) return null;
      if(root.data == p || root.data == q) return root;
      Node l = lca(root.left , p , q);
      Node r = lca(root.right ,p,q);
      if(l != null && r != null) return root;
      return (l== null) ? r : l;
        
    }
    
     void dfs(Node root , int level, int p , int q , int[] dist){
        if(root == null) return;
        if(root.data == p) dist[0] = level;
        if(root.data == q) dist[1] = level;
        dfs(root.left ,level +1 , p, q, dist );
        dfs(root.right , level +1 , p,q , dist);
        
    }
}
